(My AI combines two ideas: a convolutional neural network \(CNN\) and Monte Carlo Tree) Tj
T*
(Search \(MCTS\). The CNN is used as a policy filter: given the current 9x9 board position,) Tj
T*
(it predicts which legal moves are likely to be good candidates. MCTS then searches among) Tj
T*
(those candidates by running many simulated continuations and choosing the move with the) Tj
T*
(strongest search result. I chose this hybrid strategy because it follows the same) Tj
T*
(general direction that made AlphaGo successful: a neural network gives the search useful) Tj
T*
(guidance, while tree search prevents the move choice from depending only on a single) Tj
T*
(static evaluation.) Tj
T*
T*
(A major design decision was to keep hand-written Go knowledge in the engine instead of) Tj
T*
(relying only on the CNN. The code still scores urgent tactical moves such as captures,) Tj
T*
(saving groups in atari, connecting to friendly stones, avoiding obvious eye-filling, and) Tj
T*
(avoiding moves deep inside settled opponent territory. I also used RAVE-style rollout) Tj
T*
(information so that moves appearing in successful simulations can become more attractive) Tj
T*
(earlier in the search. This helped make the MCTS less random and more useful before the) Tj
T*
(CNN had learned enough from self-play.) Tj
T*
T*
(The CNN was trained through self-play. The first training iteration learned from) Tj
T*
(MCTS-generated games directly, using about 500 games as the starting data. After that, I) Tj
T*
(trained for 30 iterations total and used a replay window from the last 4 iterations so) Tj
T*
(the model could keep learning from recent stronger versions of itself without forgetting) Tj
T*
(too much useful older play. One challenge was balancing speed and strength: deeper MCTS) Tj
T*
(gives better decisions, but the web app still needs the AI to return a move quickly, so) Tj
T*
(the code mixes fast heuristics, a learned policy, and bounded simulations.) Tj
T*
T*
(Beyond the provided tests, I tested the AI by playing it against a classic MCTS baseline) Tj
T*
(using about 6000 simulations per move. I also tested it against GNU Go to check that it) Tj
T*
(made reasonable strategic and tactical choices against an established Go engine, not) Tj
T*
(just against my own implementation.) Tj
T*
